{{
  "@context":"https://schema.org",
  "@type":"FAQPage",
  "mainEntity":[
    {{
      "@type":"Question",
      "name":"Why does the ischial tuberosity hurt when lying down with hamstring tendinopathy and what mattress firmness helps?",
      "acceptedAnswer":{{"@type":"Answer","text":"In proximal hamstring tendinopathy (PHT), the proximal tendon attachment at the ischial tuberosity &mdash; the sitting bone &mdash; is the primary pain source. When lying supine on a mattress, the ischial tuberosities are the bony prominences that make direct contact with the sleep surface. On a firm mattress with insufficient conforming ability, the entire body weight is transmitted through a small contact area at each ischial tuberosity, generating high focal compressive stress exactly at the inflamed tendon origin. This is functionally equivalent to the compressive load that worsens PHT during prolonged sitting, reproduced in a horizontal position during sleep. The mattress mechanism has two components: (1) Pressure distribution &mdash; a mattress with a compliant comfort layer (medium to medium-firm, 5&ndash;6.5/10) distributes body weight across a larger gluteal and posterior thigh contact surface, reducing peak pressure at the ischial tuberosity itself. The tendon origin is unloaded not by avoiding contact but by spreading the force across adjacent tissue so the tuberosity carries less of the total weight. A mattress that is too soft allows the pelvis to sink into the comfort layer until the tuberosity is the last structure to make contact &mdash; paradoxically increasing focal pressure. The optimal range is medium-firm: enough conformity to engage surrounding tissue, firm enough to prevent full pelvic sink. (2) Sleep position interaction &mdash; in supine sleep, a small pillow or wedge under the affected side buttock slightly tilts the pelvis and shifts the contact point laterally, reducing ischial tuberosity contact pressure. This works best on a medium-firm surface; on a very firm surface the pillow creates a pressure ridge rather than a gradient; on a soft surface the pillow sinks into the comfort layer without effect. Mattresses with zoned support (softer in the hip zone) are particularly suited to this adjustment."}}
    }},
    {{
      "@type":"Question",
      "name":"How does hip flexion angle during side sleeping aggravate proximal hamstring tendinopathy?",
      "acceptedAnswer":{{"@type":"Answer","text":"Proximal hamstring tendinopathy originates at the ischial tuberosity &mdash; the point where the biceps femoris (long head), semimembranosus, and semitendinosus tendons converge and attach to bone. The proximal hamstring tendons are elongated when the hip is flexed (knee extended) and are at peak length at 90 degrees of hip flexion. When a patient with PHT sleeps on their side without support, the hip naturally flexes to approximately 30&ndash;60 degrees depending on body proportions and mattress surface geometry. At these hip flexion angles, the proximal hamstring tendons are under moderate tensile load &mdash; not at peak length, but well beyond the stress-shielded position of hip extension. Sustained tensile load at the ischial tuberosity origin during sleep prolongs the total daily load exposure on a tissue that needs load reduction as part of rehabilitation. Two mattress-related mechanisms amplify this: (1) Mattress-driven hip flexion increase &mdash; on a soft mattress, the hip and pelvis sink into the comfort layer while the shoulders remain higher, creating a lateral hip flexion angle beyond the natural anatomical position. The pelvis drops relative to the thorax, pulling the hip into more flexion than the patient intends. This increases tensile load at the hamstring origin through the sleep duration. A medium-firm mattress with zoned support (softer shoulders, firmer hips) prevents this pelvic sink-and-tilt, maintaining a more neutral hip flexion angle throughout the night. (2) Compressive load addition at the ischial tuberosity &mdash; in side sleeping, if the mattress does not provide adequate hip pressure relief, the greater trochanter and lateral pelvis generate discomfort that causes the patient to shift toward the prone position. In doing so, the hip extends and the compression at the ischial tuberosity increases while a rotational component is added. The ideal side-sleeping position for PHT is 20&ndash;35 degrees of hip flexion with a pillow between the knees &mdash; supported by a mattress that prevents both excessive pelvic sink (too soft) and lateral hip discomfort (too firm)."}}
    }},
    {{
      "@type":"Question",
      "name":"What is the morning gel phenomenon in hamstring tendinopathy and how does the mattress affect it?",
      "acceptedAnswer":{{"@type":"Answer","text":"The morning gel phenomenon is the characteristic first-movement stiffness experienced by tendinopathy patients &mdash; the tendon feels rigid, painful, and resistant to loading in the first 5&ndash;20 minutes after rising, before gradually improving with movement and warm-up. The mechanism is well-described in the tendinopathy literature: tendons contain a proteoglycan-enriched extracellular matrix that acts as a hydrophilic gel. During periods of minimal mechanical loading (sleep), interstitial fluid is absorbed into the tendon substance and ground-substance viscosity increases as the proteoglycan matrix swells. The first loading cycle of the day &mdash; standing, walking, stair descent, or the initial hip extension on rising from bed &mdash; forces the high-viscosity gel to resist rapid deformation, producing the characteristic painful stiffness. For proximal hamstring tendinopathy, the morning gel phenomenon is worst when the proximal tendon origin has been maintained in a loaded (hip-flexed) or compressed (ischial tuberosity contact) position throughout sleep. Mattress interventions that reduce morning gel severity: (1) Reduce ischial tuberosity compression &mdash; a mattress with adequate pressure relief in the hip zone (medium-firm, zoned coil, or pressure-distributing material like the Purple GelFlex grid) reduces the overnight compressive load at the origin, limiting the inflammatory stimulus that drives proteoglycan matrix swelling. (2) Maintain a hip-extension-leaning supine position &mdash; a medium-firm mattress allows the buttocks to rest slightly sunk into the comfort layer while the lumbar spine is supported, keeping the hip near neutral extension (not flexed) in supine sleep. This positions the proximal hamstring tendons near their stress-shielded length, reducing overnight fluid uptake into the lengthened tendon and moderating morning stiffness. (3) Prefer responsive materials &mdash; a latex or Energex foam comfort layer allows the normal micro-movements of sleep to proceed without suppression. These micro-movements provide cyclical low-level tendon loading that prevents complete gel-phase lock-up. Memory foam suppresses micro-movements and maintains the tendon in a sustained static position that worsens gel-phase viscosity by morning."}}
    }},
    {{
      "@type":"Question",
      "name":"How is proximal hamstring tendinopathy different from hamstring muscle strain and sciatica for sleep management?",
      "acceptedAnswer":{{"@type":"Answer","text":"Proximal hamstring tendinopathy (PHT), hamstring muscle strain (HMS), and sciatica are three distinct posterior thigh conditions with different anatomical targets and different sleep management priorities: (1) Proximal hamstring tendinopathy &mdash; the injury is at the tendon origin at the ischial tuberosity (collagen tissue, proximal attachment). Pain is from tendon degeneration (tendinosis) or reactive tendinopathy at the bony origin. It is a chronic overuse condition. Sleep concerns are ischial tuberosity compression in supine sleep, hip flexion tensile loading in side sleep, and morning gel phenomenon at the origin. Mattress priorities: pressure distribution at the ischial tuberosity, hip-flexion-neutral side-sleeping support, responsive materials to allow micro-movements. (2) Hamstring muscle strain &mdash; the injury is at the muscle belly (muscle fibers, typically at the musculotendinous junction of the biceps femoris) from acute traumatic overload or rapid eccentric loading (sprinting). It is an acute injury with a defined healing timeline (grade I: 1&ndash;2 weeks; grade II: 3&ndash;6 weeks; grade III: 8&ndash;16 weeks). Sleep concerns are direct pressure on the bruised or torn muscle belly in the posterior thigh, stretch in positions of full hip flexion and knee extension, and edema-related throbbing at rest in the acute phase. Mattress priorities: pressure relief along the full length of the posterior thigh, leg elevation for edema in the acute phase, avoiding hip-flexion and knee-extension combinations that lengthen the injured muscle. (3) Sciatica (lumbar nerve root compression) &mdash; the injury is at the nerve root (L4, L5, or S1) from disc herniation, foraminal stenosis, or piriformis entrapment. Pain follows a dermatomal distribution (buttock to posterior thigh to calf to foot) rather than being localized at the ischial tuberosity. Sleep concerns are nerve tension in positions of hip flexion and knee extension (straight leg raise position), lumbar disc loading in certain positions, and side-sleeping hip rotation that increases or decreases foraminal stenosis. Mattress priorities: lumbar support to maintain neutral spinal alignment, position management to reduce nerve root tension, hip alignment in side sleeping. PHT and sciatica can be confused because both produce posterior hip and thigh pain &mdash; the differentiating features are the localization to the ischial tuberosity (PHT), the absence of dermatomal distribution (PHT), and the specific worsening with sustained sitting and initial standing (PHT vs sciatica)."}}
    }},
    {{
      "@type":"Question",
      "name":"Should patients with proximal hamstring tendinopathy avoid sleeping on the affected side and what position is best?",
      "acceptedAnswer":{{"@type":"Answer","text":"Sleeping on the directly affected side (the side with PHT) places the ischial tuberosity of the affected leg in contact with the mattress surface with the full lateral body weight transmitted through it. For most PHT patients, this is acutely painful and spontaneously avoided. However, the relevant clinical question for mattress selection is not merely avoiding the affected side but managing the two alternative positions (supine and non-affected-side lateral) that PHT patients default to: (1) Supine sleeping &mdash; the most common default for PHT patients who cannot tolerate lateral pressure. In supine, both ischial tuberosities bear weight, but the load is distributed across both sides and the pelvis rests at a lower hip flexion angle than in lateral sleeping. The supine position is generally better tolerated for PHT than affected-side lateral sleeping, but requires a mattress that distributes ischial tuberosity pressure adequately rather than concentrating it at the bony prominence. A medium-firm mattress (5.5&ndash;6.5/10) with a compliant comfort layer achieves this; placing a thin pillow under the affected-side buttock slightly offloads that tuberosity by tilting the pelvis. (2) Non-affected-side lateral sleeping &mdash; the preferred lateral option, which keeps the affected ischial tuberosity on the upper (non-weighted) side. The key management issue is the hip flexion angle of the top (affected) leg: if the affected leg falls forward in hip flexion without support, the proximal hamstring tendon is placed under sustained tensile load at the origin. A pillow between the knees at 20&ndash;30 degrees of hip flexion maintains the tendon in a partially stress-shielded position. A mattress with good zoned hip pressure relief (for the non-affected lower hip) prevents the discomfort-driven position changes that could move the patient back to affected-side sleeping or prone. The optimal position for most PHT patients is supine with a pillow under both knees (reducing hip flexion angle) on a medium-firm mattress, or non-affected-side lateral with an inter-knee pillow maintaining 20&ndash;30 degrees of hip flexion."}}
    }}
  ]
}}
